<!-- ═══════════════════ LEARN PAGE ═══════════════════ -->
<div id="page-learn" class="page">
<div class="learn-page">
  <div class="learn-title">📖 How RescueNet Works</div>
  <div class="learn-sub">Complete technical guide — all features explained clearly</div>

  <div class="learn-grid">

    <!-- LOCAL MESH NETWORK -->
    <div class="learn-card cyan">
      <div class="card-icon">📶</div>
      <div class="card-title">Local Bluetooth Mesh Network</div>
      <div class="card-subtitle">Short-Range Peer-to-Peer Communication</div>
      <div class="card-body">
        A <b>mesh network</b> connects devices directly to each other — no internet, no tower, no Wi-Fi needed.<br><br>
        <b>How it works:</b>
        <div class="flow-steps">
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div>Victim's phone sends SOS via <b>Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE)</b> — range ~50–100m</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div>Nearest phone (relay node) <b>receives and re-broadcasts</b> — it doesn't need to know the destination</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div>Message <b>hops from phone to phone</b> until it reaches a device with internet</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div>Gateway device uploads the SOS to the <b>cloud rescue dashboard</b></div>
        </div>
        <br>
        <b>Why it works in forests/hills:</b> Trees, mountains, rain — none of these block Bluetooth. As long as villagers, hikers, or field workers have phones, they become the network.
        <br><br>
        <span class="tag cyan">BLE 5.0</span><span class="tag cyan">No Internet</span><span class="tag cyan">Self-healing</span><span class="tag cyan">Free</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- LORA -->
    <div class="learn-card orange">
      <div class="card-icon">📡</div>
      <div class="card-title">LoRa Long-Range Radio</div>
      <div class="card-subtitle">When Bluetooth Isn't Enough</div>
      <div class="card-body">
        <b>LoRa (Long Range)</b> is a radio technology that sends tiny data packets over enormous distances using very little power — like walkie-talkie meets internet protocol.<br><br>
        <table class="spec-table">
          <tr><td>Range</td><td><b>5–15 km</b> (line of sight), 2–5 km in forest</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Power</td><td>Runs on <b>small solar panel</b> or AA battery for months</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Data size</td><td>Up to 250 bytes per packet (SOS + GPS)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cost</td><td><b>₹800–₹2000</b> per node (vs ₹50,000+ satellite)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Frequency</td><td>865–867 MHz (India approved)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Speed</td><td>0.3–50 kbps — only for emergency alerts</td></tr>
        </table>
        <br>
        <b>When RescueNet uses LoRa:</b> When Bluetooth mesh fails (too few phones nearby), the LoRa node deployed at the village/trailhead automatically takes over and sends the SOS directly to the gateway — up to 10 km away.
        <br><br>
        <span class="tag orange">Solar Powered</span><span class="tag orange">10km Range</span><span class="tag orange">₹1500/node</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 2G SMS -->
    <div class="learn-card purple">
      <div class="card-icon">✉</div>
      <div class="card-title">2G SMS Fallback</div>
      <div class="card-subtitle">Last Resort — Always Works</div>
      <div class="card-body">
        Even in areas with zero 4G/3G, <b>2G signal often exists</b> as BSNL/Airtel maintain 2G towers for voice calls in remote India. RescueNet exploits this.<br><br>
        <b>How it works:</b>
        <div class="flow-steps">
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div>RescueNet app detects weak 2G signal (even -110 dBm is enough)</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div>SOS packet is <b>compressed to under 160 bytes</b> — exactly one SMS</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div>SMS is sent to a <b>dedicated server number</b> — no internet required</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div>Server parses the SMS and pushes alert to Rescue HQ dashboard</div>
        </div>
        <br>
        <b>SMS Packet contains:</b> GPS coordinates, victim ID, timestamp, emergency type code, battery level — all in 160 characters.
        <br><br>
        <span class="tag purple">Works on 2G</span><span class="tag purple">160 bytes</span><span class="tag purple">BSNL/Airtel</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- EMERGENCY OVERRIDE -->
    <div class="learn-card red">
      <div class="card-icon">🔴</div>
      <div class="card-title">Emergency Override</div>
      <div class="card-subtitle">When Everything Fails — Broadcast Mode</div>
      <div class="card-body">
        Emergency Override is the <b>last-resort protocol</b> activated when all normal channels fail — no mesh, no LoRa, no 2G signal.<br><br>
        <b>What it does:</b>
        <div class="flow-steps">
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><b>Broadcasts SOS simultaneously</b> on ALL available channels — BT, LoRa, 2G, Wi-Fi, ultrasonic</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div>Bypasses normal routing — goes <b>direct to all nodes</b> at max power</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><b>Flags priority CRITICAL</b> — rescue dashboard shows red alert, alarm sounds</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div>Stores SOS locally — <b>retries every 30 seconds</b> until delivered</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">5</div>Nearby phones vibrate with <b>emergency notification</b> even without internet</div>
        </div>
        <br>
        <b>Real-world use:</b> Landslide victim buried under debris. All towers down. Emergency Override keeps broadcasting until a rescue drone, vehicle, or person comes within range.
        <br><br>
        <span class="tag red">MAX POWER</span><span class="tag red">All Channels</span><span class="tag red">Auto-Retry</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- VOICE SOS -->
    <div class="learn-card green">
      <div class="card-icon">🎤</div>
      <div class="card-title">Voice SOS Input</div>
      <div class="card-subtitle">For Low-Literacy & Panic Situations</div>
      <div class="card-body">
        Typing in a panic or with injured hands is hard. RescueNet allows users to <b>speak their emergency</b> — the app converts it to text automatically.<br><br>
        <b>Why this matters in rural India:</b> Many farmers, tribal communities, and elderly people have <b>low literacy</b>. Typing "SOS at GPS 11.3°N" is impossible — but saying "Help! I fell near the waterfall" is natural.<br><br>
        <b>Technical process:</b>
        <div class="flow-steps">
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div>User holds button and speaks — app records 5–10 seconds of audio</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div>On-device <b>speech-to-text</b> converts it (works offline — no cloud needed)</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div>Text is <b>compressed and added</b> to SOS packet alongside GPS</div>
          <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div>Rescue HQ receives both the text and <b>the original audio file</b></div>
        </div>
        <br>
        <b>Supported:</b> Tamil, Telugu, Hindi, English (offline models available for all).
        <br><br>
        <span class="tag green">Offline STT</span><span class="tag green">Tamil Support</span><span class="tag green">Audio Backup</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HYBRID AUTO-SELECT -->
    <div class="learn-card yellow">
      <div class="card-icon">🔄</div>
      <div class="card-title">Hybrid Auto-Select Mode</div>
      <div class="card-subtitle">The Brain — Picks Best Channel Automatically</div>
      <div class="card-body">
        RescueNet doesn't make users choose a mode. In Hybrid mode, <b>the app decides in real time</b> which channel gives the fastest, most reliable delivery.<br><br>
        <b>Decision logic (runs every 5 seconds):</b>
        <table class="spec-table">
          <tr><td>Check 1</td><td>BT mesh peers available? → Use <b>Mesh</b></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Check 2</td><td>LoRa node in range? → Use <b>LoRa</b></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Check 3</td><td>2G signal detected? → Use <b>SMS Fallback</b></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Check 4</td><td>Everything failed? → <b>Emergency Override</b></td></tr>
        </table>
        <br>
        <b>Why it matters:</b> A hiker might start with Bluetooth mesh, walk deeper where only LoRa works, then descend to a valley with 2G. The app switches <b>automatically, seamlessly</b> — the user just presses SOS once.
        <br><br>
        <span class="tag yellow">Auto-Switch</span><span class="tag yellow">Real-Time</span><span class="tag yellow">Zero Config</span>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

